entry.title: Eliminate the manual ChromeDriver release process
entry.content:
As of M115, ChromeDriver is fully integrated into the Chrome release

process. Across all release channels (Stable, Beta, Dev, Canary),

every Chrome release that gets pushed to users automatically gets a

correspondingly-versioned ChromeDriver release, available for

download via Chrome for Testing infrastructure [1].



This significantly simplifies the status quo & solves a number of

issues:



1. It completely eliminates the manual ChromeDriver release process.

2. It aligns ChromeDriver releases with Chrome releases.

3. It makes it significantly easier for users to download matching

Chrome for Testing + ChromeDriver binaries.



This patch removes any scripts and references to the old ChromeDriver

release process.



Announcement: https://groups.google.com/g/chromedriver-users/c/clpipqvOGjE



[1]: https://googlechromelabs.github.io/chrome-for-testing/



Doc: go/chromedriver:cft (Google-internal)

entry.title: PreloadingDevTools: Add holdbacks by PreloadingConfig to Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated
entry.content:
Historically, preloading was controlled by coarse-grained feature flags

PreloadingHoldback/Prerender2Holdback. We introduced PreloadingConfig

[1] and we are adopting more fine-grained control. For more details,

see [2] and [3].



This CL adds disabledByHoldbackPrefetchSpeculationRules and

disabledByHoldbackPrerenderSpeculationRules to the CDP event

Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated.



Note that by historical reason, DevTools frontend had gotten holdback

status with SystemInfo.getFeatureState [4]. This CL aggregates

"disabled" reasons to Preload.preloadEnabledStateUpdated and allows

DevTools frontend to listen only the event once we deprecate the old

flags.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4237269

[2] https://groups.google.com/a/google.com/g/chrome-prerendering/c/dIyQe68J3VQ/m/ghfY-bXjAAAJ

entry.title: Incognito Reauth: Fix reauth screen not restored when activity is killed
entry.content:
Under memory pressure (emulated by the "Don't keep activities" setting), IncognitoReauthController gets killed after starting the reauthentication flow. When restored, savedInstanceState is checked for incognitoReauthPending when re-initializing the IncognitoReauthController, to determine whether to resume the reauthentication flow.



The problem lies when the SavedInstanceState is reset in

ChromeTabbedActivity::onStartWithNative which sets it to null before it

is checked for the incognitoReauthPending key in

RootUiCoordinator::onFinishNativeInitialization, making

mIsIncognitoReauthPendingOnRestore in IncognitoReauthController always

return false and the reauth screen not getting restored when the

activity is killed.



This CL saves the incognitoReauthPending key value from

SavedInstanceState in the the constructor of RootUiCoordinator before

it is reset.



Demo: https://drive.google.com/file/d/16nBDAFA3bIk065EsGGmynMLTY_zU7Uop/view?usp=sharing

entry.title: Disable ARC exception code
entry.content:
By default, ARC generates exception handlers in Objective-C++ code so

that ARC-managed variables are released properly in the presence of

exceptions.



Exceptions are already banned in Chromium code for C++, so these extra

exception handlers are not needed.



In Objective-C code, exception handling is only used to wrap APIs that

are known to throw, so adding additional handlers for exception safety

is not needed, as Chromium will be crashing anyway.



Therefore, when enabling ARC, disable these unwanted exception

handlers.



Fixed: 1457378

entry.title: DevTools: allow running addScriptToEvaluateOnNewDocument for existing contexts
entry.content:
Currently, during auto-attach to a target while the target is paused there is no way to run a script for an isolated world that will be created once the target is unpaused. Runtime.evaluate requires a contextId which can only be retried after the target is unpaused. This CL adds the flag to opt-in into running the script for "existing" documents immediately for the following reasons:



1) worlds is a Blink feature and should not be exposed in the Runtime domain (V8 feature).

2) there is a precedent in addScriptToEvaluateOnNewDocument for running the scripts for paused new windows already.



This parameters allows running the script immediately even if the target is not paused and while it is not required for the current issue with auto-attach and isolated worlds it might be useful on its own because addScriptToEvaluateOnNewDocument calls are often followed by the Runtime.evaluate calls with the same script.



Fixed: 1449849

entry.title: Keep selection non-empty when selection dragging in Textfield.
entry.content:
Don't allow the selection to become empty when dragging selection

handles or performing a long/double press drag selection gesture in

views::Textfield. This way, we can avoid the handles being placed right

next to each other (which looks a bit strange, see b:286346616).



This also helps makes the views::Textfield selection dragging behaviour

be a bit more consistent with blink::DirectionGranularityStrategy:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:third_party/blink/renderer/core/editing/granularity_strategy.cc;l=157;drc=047c7dc4ee1ce908d7fea38ca063fa2f80f92c77

`AuthenticatorAssertionResponse`, to mirror

`AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`.
